[b]Bayesian Trend Factor [WavesUnchained][/b]

[b]What it does[/b]
Bayesian Trend Factor is a Bayesian-inspired probabilistic trend-quality filter. It maps the current trend thesis to a signed [b]-100..+100[/b] factor and a separate [b]0..100[/b] confidence reading. It tells you whether the active trend context is clean enough to trust, and includes optional Pullback / Continuation signals plus HAMA-style smoothed trend candles.

[b]Evidence blocks[/b]
[list]
[*][b]Direction[/b] — linear-regression slope normalized by ATR
[*][b]Strength[/b] — ADX, Kaufman Efficiency Ratio and Regression R2
[*][b]Structure[/b] — swing HH/HL or LL/LH structure
[*][b]Volatility[/b] — ATR percentile as a quality multiplier only, not direction
[*][b]Exhaustion[/b] — overextension plus rejection or momentum fade as a penalty
[/list]

Direction, gated strength, aged structure and exhaustion are converted into pseudo probabilities, weighted and fused through log-odds. Volatility is deliberately kept out of direction and only scales the quality of the final thesis. The final factor is then moderated by confidence, so weak evidence is softened rather than treated as a clean trend call.

[b]Interpretation[/b]
[list]
[*][b]+80 to +100[/b] — strong bullish trend
[*][b]+55 to +79[/b] — bullish trend active
[*][b]-54 to +54[/b] — neutral, transition or low-quality trend
[*][b]-55 to -79[/b] — bearish trend active
[*][b]-80 to -100[/b] — strong bearish trend
[/list]

[b]State hysteresis[/b]
Bull/bear states activate at the main trend threshold and exit only once the factor falls back through the lower exit threshold. This reduces threshold flicker. The dashboard shows the final smoothed Bull Probability separately from the raw Bull Probability.

[b]Features[/b]
[list]
[*]Signed Trend Factor plus separate Confidence
[*]Configurable evidence weights and thresholds
[*]Volatility quality multiplier instead of directional volatility evidence
[*]Direction gate for Strength evidence and age decay for swing Structure
[*]Exhaustion malus based on stretch plus rejection or momentum fade
[*]Short factor smoothing to reduce state flicker
[*]Trend-state hysteresis using separate activation and exit thresholds
[*]Final Bull/Bear probability derived from the smoothed factor, with raw probability exposed for diagnostics
[*]Fair Path regression line with optional +/-2 ATR bands
[*]Candle coloring by trend state
[*]Optional candle score labels on threshold or large-score changes
[*]Optional Pullback / Continuation module with PB setup labels and CONT trigger labels, including hover explanations
[*]Optional smoothed overlay candles via plotcandle(), with BTF-gradient or smoothed-body-direction coloring
[*]Dashboard with state, confidence, probabilities and evidence scores
[*]Alerts for bull/bear activation, strong trend states, neutral transition, pullback setups and continuation triggers
[/list]

[b]Trend Candles[/b]
The Trend Candles module draws a HAMA-style smoothed candle layer. Smoothed open uses the prior bar midpoint, smoothed close uses OHLC4, and smoothed high/low use EMA-filtered extremes clamped around the smoothed body. In BTF Gradient mode, the candle color follows the signed Trend Factor; in Smoothed Candle Direction mode, candle color follows the smoothed candle body direction and the MA line uses an advance/decline gradient. Wicks and borders are lightly transparent so range information stays visible.

[b]Pullback / Continuation module[/b]
The continuation layer is gated by BTF trend direction and confidence. A [b]PB[/b] label appears only when price returns from above/below the Pullback EMA and Fair Path into a controlled pullback zone inside an active trend. Pullback depth is measured from a prior impulse reference. A [b]CONT[/b] label fires only when structure still holds and price confirms continuation through an EMA reclaim, one-bar micro-BOS or rejection wick. PB and CONT labels include hover explanations; the CONT label also includes the continuation score on a 0..10 scale.

[b]How to use[/b]
Use the base factor as a trend-quality filter. Use CONT labels only in the direction of an already active BTF trend. Neutral reads warn that the trend is transitional, conflicted or not clean enough.

